µJEµC3In the year 1988, the danish musician Jesper Kyd (http://jesperkyd.com) began his career in the Amiga demoscene. Without a bigger recognition, he was already tracking for some years on the C64. But being not popular wasn´t a problem anymore, after he changed the computer he was working with, it was more on the contrary.

The most wellknown productions he and his danish friend, Michael Balle, made under the glorious flag of TSL DK (= The Silents danish devision), were the "Global Trash" ftp://totem.fix.no/pub/kyd-balle/video/gtrash.mpg demo in 1990, and the milestone "Hardwired" in 1991. Kyd delivered the demotune, Balle as usual the graphics - the team Kyd & Balle was a brand. A brand everybody knew of at that time.

One year later they´ve set the first stone in the wall of the history of video demos with their TP contribution "Global Trash II".

The continuation of "Global Trash" was the first presented demo ever, which wasn´t executed on a computer, but still with the support of various computer platforms. Michael Balle was playing around with expensive machines that he was allowed to use from a danish film company. Therefore thanks to this fact and his creativity, he was able to push the frontiers of possible effects far forwards!! But however, until now, this video production is recognized as the first known wilddemo ever. It´s the father and/or mother of all those wilddemos, that nowadays cross our streets quite frequently.

But that is far from being it all, Jesper later became a rather impressive musician for countless games on PC and Sega Megadrive, like for example "MDK II" or "Hitmen 2", which were both sold successfully. 

We should also mention his activities for the american film industry, where he created soundtracks for various movies. The JP/PAiN staff decided to choose a real "cool" location for our gathering. We spoke with him in the wasteland of Alaska, just a hundred feets away from where Zerox and Lord Helmet have taken their last breaths in the scenish tale "D.i.s.c tours in Alaska".

As his studio is located in New York city, we certainly wanted to know his personal impressions about the ongoins at the 11th of September. But enough spoken, let us just start the show!

