µC5Ghandy:µC4 First of all: How came it that you started composing on the Amiga? You began to learn to play piano quite early, with nine years if I remember correctly, but why composing on a cold and technical machine when you have a warm sounding piano in your flat? What did hit your interest and why?

µC5JK:µC4 There was many things I found interesting. The C64 was the first time I started noticing computer music. I was playing a ton of C64 games and and when the music connected perfectly with the game experience (like the scores of Martin Galway, Fred Gray, Rob Hubbard, Tim Follin etc) I just thought this was the most amazing thing. I got a hold of a music program and started converting Galway songs into this program. I slowly started learning and did some 200 songs on the C64 before moving to the Amiga.

I also love the fact the when you work with computers and music you are on the forefront of something new. You are part of the cutting edge and by programming these instruments you can create atmospheres and sounds that have never been heard before

µC5Ghandy:µC4 It didn´t take that long and after starting to track on C64 and Amiga, you were already involved in a huge number of scenerelated productions. How do you explain yourself your success? What is so different when it comes to your music compared to other composers? At the late 80s and early 90s really a lot people were tracking on the miggy, why did coders choose you so often?

µC5JK:µC4
I don't really know... hm, I have never been to concerned with style and technical "tracking" abilities. Many Amiga composers focused on technique, but I was always more interesting in creating new atmospheres and experiments that hadn't been done before. I think this makes my music more original. Amiga musicians didn't always like my music, because when you take a look at the music in a music program, it's quite simple. My music comes from the samples and the way they are arranged. And this is often done in a totally spontaneous way. It has been quite difficult to cut back on the spontaneous way that I write music, in order for me to create more precise music for projects such as films. In films every single note has to fit with the atmosphere of what happens on the screen.

µC5Ghandy:µC4 Many sceners try with more or less success to enter the game industry. I´m sure still many readers still haven´t heard the story how it all began and in which projects you were and are involved!

µC5JK:µC4
Well, I did some game scores way back for a bunch of Amiga games. I wrote around 6 scores, but most were unreleased or cancelled. I'm glad all this failure happened early on, since it's harder to deal with 6 straight failures when you are older and need these deals for survival. Then my first game was released on the Amiga. A game called USS John Young. I started working with Crionics and we started doing games. One we finished, but it was never released. (I wrote the mod TikobII for this game) Then we bought some Sega Genesis/Megadrive development kits and started writing Genesis games instead of Amiga games. Our first completed game became Subterrania. Sega liked this game and decided to release it. It became a moderate hit selling about 250.000 copies. Then we moved to Boston and later Hollywood. The next 5 scores I wrote were all for Sega Genesis. We programmed our own music program for the Genesis and this program was amazing. It could play back FM sounds in CD quality. This is much better than Sega's own music program, which mainly played back samples in a very low quality.

