µC5Ghandy:µC4 How did you get the connection to the film industry? Please tell us for which kind of movies you are doing the soundtrack. It would be quite interesting for me to hear what differences you see between making music for a demo, a commercial game or a movie. Where do you have the most freedom, what makes the most fun and money?

µC5JK:µC4 I am connected with the film industry here in NYC and just finished another film score. This was the biggest music project I have ever been part of. I wrote almost 2 hours of music for this film. It's a gangster film, independently produced in Hollywood and Germany.

One of my other films, a comedy/mystery film called Death of a Saleswoman is currently playing at film festivals here in the US.

As to where I have the most fun, that's not simply a question of games or films. Generally I have more freedom when writing game scores. I always try to come up with something as different and original as possible and game designers welcome this.  Examples are my scores for MDK2, Hitman Series, The Nations, Brute Force & Freedom. Other times you are asked to come up with music that fits a certain criteria, such as my scores for Minority Report and Messiah.

I like writing scores when you are given creative freedom. This often happens with games. With films, directors and producers often know what they are looking for and you have to squeeze your music style into that criteria, while still trying to remain original and unique. Not exactly easy :) This might be one reason why there are so many generic film scores out there. If you are a composer with an unique sound, you most try to hold on to this, since writing generic scores are easy and anyone can learn to do it. If you have your own sound, you will be ahead of the pack. Then you just have to focus on controlling/taming your unique style/sound a bit when needed. Or don't tame it and start releasing music trough the record industry :)

µC5Ghandy:µC4 What about Mikael Balle, what is he nowadays doing? Do you sometimes miss the good old times? If you would have the opportunity to join a timemachine, would you use it in order to dive into the glorious times of the scene again? What does the scene offer you today? Have you seen any recent productions on PC or Amiga ? Maybe by using an emulator etc.

µC5JK:µC4 Mikael is doing great. He just started his own company in Copenhagen, which focuses on computer graphic. We just did a new video together, which was made for a presentation of my music, for the Crown Prince of Denmark. If I had a time capsule I wouldn't use it yet. I believe the best is yet to come.

Yeah I watch PC demos once in a while. Haujobb does some nice stuff and Silents are also kicking some ass again.

µC5Ghandy:µC4 By creating your video demo you two have opened the gates for a completely new subscene, the wilddemo scene to be more precise. Did you two have a slight idea what would follow after "Global Trash II"? Which programs/computers did you use to get it real? Only Amiga power or did you also "ab"-use some commercial programs on Mac or Pc ?

µC5JK:µC4 I don't think we knew what to think about "Global Trash 2", expect we thought it was cool. It really was a crazy experiment and it worked out. We used all kind of equipment, since Mikael worked at a major Danish film company. We had access to some major equipment and massive computers.

It's great to know that we have been able to contribute something to the scene, something that goes beyond releasing demos. Also I don't recall hearing or seeing any concerts at demo parties until after our concert... and then in the middle of all this craziness we release Hardwired. It certainly was crazy times. Now I get to work with 97 piece orchestras and 60 piece choirs, so things are just as insane (if not more) but in a very very different way. The pressure of a successful recording is suddenly present, and knowing how much money is spent on such recordings can make you a bit paranoid ;)

µC5Ghandy:µC4 As you have your studio in New York, I would like to know about your remembrance of the 11th of September. Have you been present in NY when it happened? What did change in your town or generally in the USA since that date? Is it now impossible to feel secure after that? What do you think about your presidents´ plans to conquer Iraque ?

µC5JK:µC4 I was mixing Hitman 2 in Europe at the time. It was unreal. We saw it happen live on TV, since my wife called the studio the moment the first tower was struck. We had to finish up the mixing, and kept turning the TV on and off. At the moment it happened we were working on the tracks for the missions in the middle east. Big heroic music and that felt very strange, since we knew it was a terror attack from somewhere in the middle east. We couldn't get back home, since Manhattan had been closed of and stayed this way for days. When driving back to Manhattan you saw all this smoke above downtown. It's hard to explain how I felt. Once back my next score was for Freedom: The Battle for Liberty Island, which is about freedom fighters fighting a regime who wants to take over the world. This came takes place in New York.

I feel I got a lot of my emotions out trough this music. The score was later recorded in Budapest with a the Hungarian Radio Choir. Manhattan has changed quite a bit. For one, the people who live here (not the tourists, they are usually the rude ones) are much more friendly. Friendlier than any other US city I have been to.

As far as the plans to conquer Iraq, I am not happy with Bush and his war efforts. Still, it's a tough desicion. Living in Manhattan we of all people are probably the next target for terror. If we can learn to live with this fear, perhaps the rest of the US could learn to live with the fear of Iraq, until some proof have been found that he is indeed planning or building weapons for some kind of attack.

µC5Ghandy:µC4 What are your future plans? Is there still something you could reach? I mean, you have done the soundtrack for some of the most important games as "MDK II", "Hitman 2", etc., you are doing music for commercial movies, still not such big projects, but it´s quite impressive. Are there any dreams you are working for? What is your biggest dream, what is the next small step ?

µC5JK:µC4 There are many things I would like to do. I really don't want to mention them...they might appear quite silly, unless I achieve them...Still I have been working with my dance music band and would love to see some of this music released. I have zero contacts in that part of the record industry though, since the only CDs I have out in stores are soundtracks.

µC5Ghandy:µC4 Any hints you could give other musicians that feel talented themselfs and would like to participate in the game industry?? What are possible mistakes you could make while contacting them?

When contacting game companies it's important not to appear to desperate. Don't say stuff like "I'll do anything" or "you don't have to pay me". They will think that since you don't charge any money perhaps you don't think your music is worth any money. Still, they may say we love your stuff, but have no cash and then I would go ahead with it. Just be sure you remain the copyright of your music or some other kind of payment like royalties etc.

